{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480131"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:37:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.11,0.79,0.01,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"16"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81548"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/16"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"6399"},{"type":"tags","id":"6473"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44447"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81548"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with an eight-hour history of sudden onset severe left scrotal pain. He denies any trauma. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The left hemiscrotum is swollen, tender and elevated with a high-riding testis that is difficult to palpate. The left spermatic cord is thickened and tender. The cremasteric reflex is absent on the left. The right testis lies horizontally and is non-tender with a normal epididymis and intact cremasteric reflex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Analgesia and review in 24 hours","Urgent scrotal ultrasound","Surgical exploration","Urinalysis and urine culture","Doppler ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of testicular torsion including sudden onset severe scrotal pain, high-riding testis, absent cremasteric reflex, and thickened spermatic cord. While testicular torsion is more common in adolescents, it can occur at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step when there is high clinical suspicion of testicular torsion. With symptoms present for eight hours, there is only about a 20% chance of testicular salvage, but immediate surgery still offers the best chance. If the testis is non-viable, orchidectomy will be performed. Given the horizontal lie of the contralateral testis, bilateral orchidopexy would be indicated to prevent future torsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalgesia and review in 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would result in certain testicular loss if torsion is present. Any delay in treatment significantly reduces the chance of salvage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent scrotal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EDoppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E, while useful diagnostic tools in cases of uncertain diagnosis, should not delay surgical exploration when clinical features strongly suggest torsion. The time taken to arrange and perform imaging could compromise testicular viability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinalysis and urine culture\u003C/strong\u003E might be appropriate in cases where epididymo-orchitis is suspected, but the acute onset and examination findings in this case are classic for torsion rather than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe testis has the best chance of survival if detorsion occurs within 6 hours of symptom onset. After 12 hours, the salvage rate drops to less than 10%. Therefore, time is critical in the management of suspected testicular torsion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Testicular torsion is a surgical emergency requiring immediate exploration without imaging delay if clinical suspicion is high.","Key clinical features of testicular torsion include acute severe scrotal pain, high-riding testis, absent cremasteric reflex, and thickened spermatic cord.","The chance of testicular salvage decreases dramatically after 6 hours of torsion."],"references":["Jeffries MT, Cox AC, Gupta A, et al. The management of acute testicular pain in children and adolescents. BMJ 2015; 350:h1563."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66902"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66902"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T11:41:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T11:43:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"16"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81548"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"